# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: drone-ci
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:drone-ci/build-automation] Build automation encompasses both sequencing build operations via non-interactive interface tools and running builds on a shared server.
[src:drone-ci/build-automation] Build automation tools allow sequencing the tasks of building software via a non-interactive interface.
[src:drone-ci/build-automation] A *build system* or *build automation tool* is a programming tool or set of tools that automate the compiling and linking of source code into an executable program or library.
[src:drone-ci/build-automation] They streamline the software development process by managing dependencies, resolving conflicts, and ensuring consistent builds across different environments.
[src:drone-ci/build-automation] When software projects grow complex, their build steps may involve multiple programming languages or compiling units, making manual build processes increasingly cumbersome.
[src:drone-ci/build-automation] Dependencies between code components necessitate careful ordering and potentially different tools for each piece.
[src:drone-ci/build-automation] Managing these dependencies manually can quickly lead to version conflicts, stale binaries, and difficulty tracking updates, making solutions such as shell scripts too difficult to maintain.
[src:drone-ci/build-automation] While individual developers might compile code directly, a robust build system is foundational to efficient software development in large organizations and teams, where automated builds become commonplace and most builds are triggered automatically rather than manually.
[src:drone-ci/build-automation] Given the essential role of build systems, it is said that they act as "repositories of essential build knowledge".
[src:drone-ci/build-automation] They effectively eliminate roadblocks and accelerate development velocity by enabling engineers to share resources and results.
[src:drone-ci/build-automation] An incremental build is a process within a build system where build tools use an incremental compiler to recompile only the parts of a software project that have changed since the last build, rather than rebuilding everything from scratch.
[src:drone-ci/build-automation] This optimization reduces build time by leveraging dependency tracking, caching, and selective compilation.
[src:drone-ci/build-automation] Incremental builds are especially valuable in large-scale software projects, where recompiling the entire codebase can be time-consuming and resource-intensive.
[src:drone-ci/build-automation] By identifying and compiling only the modified components—such as source files, libraries, or modules—the build system ensures faster iteration cycles, enabling developers to test and debug changes more efficiently.
[src:drone-ci/build-automation] The process relies on a dependency graph, which maps relationships between files, modules, or components in the project.
[src:drone-ci/build-automation] When a change is detected, the build system traverses this graph to determine which parts of the project are affected and need to be recompiled.
[src:drone-ci/build-automation] Modern build tools, such as Make, Gradle and Bazel, often incorporate incremental build capabilities to streamline development workflows.
[src:drone-ci/build-automation] While incremental builds offer significant performance advantages, they also introduce challenges, such as ensuring the accuracy of dependency tracking and avoiding stale or inconsistent build artifacts.
[src:drone-ci/build-automation] To address these issues, some build systems provide mechanisms for "clean builds," which rebuild the entire project from scratch to guarantee correctness when necessary.
[src:drone-ci/build-automation] Because of this issue, incremental builds are rarely used in continuous integration systems, where correctness is preferred to compilation speed.
[src:drone-ci/build-automation] Tools such as Make can be used via custom configuration file or using the command-line.
[src:drone-ci/build-automation] Custom tools such as shell scripts can also be used, although they become increasingly cumbersome as the codebase grows more complex.
[src:drone-ci/build-automation] Some tools, such as shell scripts, are task-oriented declarative programming.
[src:drone-ci/build-automation] They encode sequences of commands to perform with usually minimal conditional logic.
[src:drone-ci/build-automation] Some tools, such as Make are product-oriented.
[src:drone-ci/build-automation] They build a product, a.k.a. target, based on configured dependencies.
[src:drone-ci/build-automation] A build server is a server setup to run builds.
[src:drone-ci/build-automation] In contrast to a personal computer, a server allows for a more consistent and available build environment.
[src:drone-ci/build-automation] Traditionally, a build server was a local computer dedicated as a shared resource instead of used as a personal computer.
[src:drone-ci/build-automation] Today, there are many cloud computing, software as a service (SaaS) websites for building.
[src:drone-ci/build-automation] A continuous integration server is a build server that is setup to build in a relatively frequent way, often on each code commit.
[src:drone-ci/build-automation] A build server may also be incorporated into a tool for application release automation (ARA) or application lifecycle management (ALM).
[src:drone-ci/build-automation] Automating the build process is a required step for implementing continuous integration and continuous delivery (CI/CD), all of which are considered best practices for software development.
[src:drone-ci/container-virtualization] In software engineering, **containerization** is operating-system-level virtualization or application-level virtualization over multiple resources so that software applications can run in isolated user spaces called *containers* in any cloud or non-cloud environment, regardless of type or vendor.
[src:drone-ci/container-virtualization] The term "container" has different meanings in different contexts, and it is important to ensure that the intended definition aligns with the audience's understanding.
[src:drone-ci/container-virtualization] Each *container* is basically a fully functional and portable cloud or non-cloud computing environment surrounding the application and keeping it independent of other environments running in parallel.
[src:drone-ci/container-virtualization] Individually, each container simulates a different software application and runs isolated processes by bundling related configuration files, libraries and dependencies.
[src:drone-ci/container-virtualization] But, collectively, multiple containers share a common operating system kernel (OS).
[src:drone-ci/container-virtualization] In recent times, containerization technology has been widely adopted by cloud computing platforms like Amazon Web Services, Microsoft Azure, Google Cloud Platform, and IBM Cloud.
[src:drone-ci/container-virtualization] Containerization has also been pursued by the U.S.
[src:drone-ci/container-virtualization] Department of Defense as a way of more rapidly developing and fielding software updates, with first application in its F-22 air superiority fighter.
[src:drone-ci/container-virtualization] Container orchestration or container management is mostly used in the context of application containers.
[src:drone-ci/container-virtualization] Implementations providing such orchestration include Kubernetes and Docker swarm.
[src:drone-ci/container-virtualization] This includes functionality to create a cluster, to upgrade the software or repair it, balance the load between existing instances, scale by starting or stopping instances to adapt to the number of users, to log activities and monitor produced logs or the application itself by querying sensors.
[src:drone-ci/container-virtualization] Open-source implementations of such software include OKD and Rancher.
[src:drone-ci/container-virtualization] Quite a number of companies provide container cluster management as a managed service, like Alibaba, Amazon, Google, and Microsoft.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] The earliest known work (1989) on continuous integration was the Infuse environment developed by G.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] In 1997, Kent Beck and Ron Jeffries invented extreme programming (XP) while on the Chrysler Comprehensive Compensation System project, including continuous integration.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] Beck published about continuous integration in 1998, emphasising the importance of face-to-face communication over technological support.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] In 1999, Beck elaborated more in his first full book on Extreme Programming.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] CruiseControl, one of the first open-source CI tools, was released in 2001.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] In 2010, Timothy Fitz published an article detailing how IMVU's engineering team had built and been using the first practical CD system.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] While his post was originally met with skepticism, it quickly caught on and found widespread adoption as part of the lean software development methodology, also based on IMVU.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] The core activities of CI are that developers co-locate code changes in a shared, integration area frequently and that the resulting integrated codebase is verified for correctness.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] The first part generally involves merging changes to a common version control branch.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] The second part generally involves automated processes including: building, testing and many other processes.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] Typically, a server builds from the integration area frequently, i.e. after each commit or periodically, like once a day.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] The server may perform quality control checks such as running unit tests and collect software quality metrics via processes such as static analysis and performance testing.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] Build automation tools automate building.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI recommend that a single command should have the capability of building the system.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] Automation often includes automating the integration, which often includes deployment into a production-like environment.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] In many cases, the build script not only compiles binaries but also generates documentation, website pages, statistics and distribution media (such as Debian DEB, Red Hat RPM or Windows MSI files).
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] CI requires the version control system to support atomic commits; in other words, all of a developer's changes are handled as a single commit.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] When making a code change, a developer creates a branch that is a copy of the current codebase.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] As other changes are committed to the repository, this copy diverges from the latest version.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] The longer development continues on a branch without merging to the integration branch, the greater the risk of multiple integration conflicts and failures when the developer branch is eventually merged back.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] When developers submit code to the repository they must first update their code to reflect the changes in the repository since they took their copy.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] The more changes the repository contains, the more work developers must do before submitting their own changes.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] Eventually, the repository may become so different from the developers' baselines that they enter what is sometimes referred to as "merge hell", or "integration hell", where the time it takes to integrate exceeds the time it took to make their original changes.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI suggest that developers should use test-driven development and to ensure that all unit tests pass locally before committing to the integration branch so that one developer's work does not break another developer's copy.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] Incomplete features can be disabled before committing, using feature toggles.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] Continuous delivery ensures the software checked in on an integration branch is always in a state that can be deployed to users, and continuous deployment automates the deployment process.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI recommend storing all files and information needed for building in version control (for git a *repository*), and that the system should be buildable from a fresh checkout and not require additional dependencies.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] Martin Fowler recommends that all developers commit to the same integration branch.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] Developers can reduce the effort of resolving conflicting changes by synchronizing changes with each other frequently, at least daily.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] Checking in a week's worth of work risks conflict both in likelihood of occurrence and complexity to resolve.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] Relatively small conflicts are significantly easier to resolve than larger ones.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] Integrating (committing) changes at least once a day is considered good practice, and more often better.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] Building daily, if not more often, is generally recommended.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] The system should build commits to the current working version to verify that they integrate correctly.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] A common practice is to use Automated Continuous Integration, although this may be done manually.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] Automated continuous integration employs a continuous integration server or daemon to monitor the revision control system for changes, then automatically run the build process.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] When fixing a bug, it is a good practice to push a test case that reproduces the bug.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] This prevents the fix from being reverted and the bug from reappearing, which is known as a regression.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] The build needs to complete rapidly so that if there is a problem with integration, it is quickly identified.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] Having a test environment can lead to failures in tested systems when they deploy in the production environment because the production environment may differ from the test environment in a significant way.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] However, building a replica of a production environment is cost-prohibitive.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] Instead, the test environment or a separate pre-production environment ("staging") should be built to be a scalable version of the production environment to alleviate costs while maintaining technology stack composition and nuances.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] Within these test environments, service virtualisation is commonly used to obtain on-demand access to dependencies (e.g., APIs, third-party applications, services, mainframes, etc.) that are beyond the team's control, still evolving, or too complex to configure in a virtual test lab.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] Making builds readily available to stakeholders and testers can reduce the amount of rework necessary when rebuilding a feature that doesn't meet requirements.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] Additionally, early testing reduces the chances that defects survive until deployment.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] Finding errors earlier can reduce the amount of work necessary to resolve them.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] All programmers should start the day by updating the project from the repository.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] That way, they will all stay up to date.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] It should be easy to find out whether the build breaks and, if so, who made the relevant change and what that change was.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] Most CI systems allow the running of scripts after a build finishes.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] In most situations, it is possible to write a script to deploy the application to a live test server that everyone can look at.
[src:drone-ci/continuous-integration] A further advance in this way of thinking is continuous deployment, which calls for the software to be deployed directly into production, often with additional automation to prevent defects or regressions.
[src:drone-ci/docs-drone-io] Drone by Harness™ is a modern Continuous Integration platform that empowers busy teams to automate their build, test and release workflows using a powerful, cloud native pipeline engine.
[src:drone-ci/docs-drone-io] Drone comes in two distributions: the Enterprise Edition and the Community Edition.
[src:drone-ci/pipeline-overview] Pipelines help you automate steps in your software delivery process, such as initiating code builds, running automated tests, and deploying to a staging or production environment.
[src:drone-ci/pipeline-overview] Pipeline execution is triggered by a source code repository.
[src:drone-ci/pipeline-overview] A change in code triggers a webhook to Drone which runs the corresponding pipeline.
[src:drone-ci/pipeline-overview] Other common triggers include automatically scheduled or user-initiated workflows.
[src:drone-ci/pipeline-overview] Pipelines are configured by placing a `.drone.yml` file in the root of your git repository.
[src:drone-ci/pipeline-overview] The yaml syntax is designed to be easy to read and expressive so that anyone viewing the repository can understand the workflow.
